Subject: The Last Dance - Episode 2
Description: Michael Jordan is left to begin the 1997-98 season without his injured sidekick Scottie Pippen, whose contract dispute with the Bulls' front office reaches a fever pitch as the team gets off to one of the worst starts of its championship runs.

Subject: The Last Dance - Episode 3
Description: Once a key member of the hated Detroit Pistons' ``Bad Boys`` championship teams that brutalized Michael Jordan, Dennis Rodman is virtually all Jordan can count on in the early months of the 1997-98 season.

Subject: The Last Dance - Episode 4
Description: In what management insists is Phil Jackson's final season in Chicago as head coach of the Bulls, he continues to seem like the only one who can steer this unique, singular collection of talent to another title.

Subject: The Last Dance - Episode 5
Description: As Michael Jordan's fame peaked to unparalleled levels in the early 1990s in the wake of consecutive NBA titles and a starring role on the Olympic Dream Team, his image as ``Air Jordan`` made him a profoundly significant cultural figure.

Subject: The Last Dance - Episode 6
Description: With Michael Jordan's extraordinary fame came extraordinary scrutiny, and in 1993, it all felt like it came to a head with the Chicago Bulls' pursuit of a third straight title shadowed by question marks about Jordan's gambling.

Subject: Southern Hoops: A History of SEC Basketball - Part Five (1990-1998)
Description: Arkansas joins the SEC and becomes one of the conference's top teams, led by fiery coach Nolan Richardson and his ``40 Minutes of Hell'' attack. Kentucky returns to prominence, and at Tennessee, Pat Summitt wins three straight NCAA titles.

Subject: Southern Hoops: A History of SEC Basketball - Part Four (1980-1989)
Description: Georgia's Dominique Wilkins and Auburn's Charles Barkley headline the SEC's successes in the early 1980s, while LSU's Dale Brown takes two teams to the Final Four. Pat Summitt wins her first two national titles at Tennessee.

Subject: Southern Hoops: A History of SEC Basketball - Part Three (1971-1979)
Description: Dale Brown brings an infectious personality to LSU while Pat Summitt begins her legendary coaching career at Tennessee. And the year after Adolph Rupp's death in 1977, his successor Joe B. Hall leads Kentucky to its first NCAA title in 20 years.

Subject: Southern Hoops: A History of SEC Basketball - Part Two (1960-1970)
Description: Texas Western's historic win over Adolph Rupp's Kentucky team in the 1966 NCAA final marks a turning point in the SEC. Vanderbilt's Perry Wallace becomes the conference's first Black player, while at LSU, Pete Maravich rewrites the record books.
